{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569417"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22135"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22135"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.8,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15097"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109112"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15097"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91470"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"2798"},{"type":"tags","id":"2896"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39505"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109112"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman is admitted to hospital under the General Medicine team with a three-week history of palpitations, heat intolerance, and unintentional weight loss. She reports a painless swelling in the front of her neck that she first noticed a few months ago. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a primary school teacher and does not smoke or use substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a fine bilateral tremor in both hands. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 128/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.9\u00b0C. There is a palpable, non-tender nodule in the right lobe of the thyroid gland. No cervical lymphadenopathy is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone \u0026lt;0.01 mIU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFree thyroxine 32 pmol/L (10-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFree triiodothyronine 9.0 pmol/L (3.0-6.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to determine the functional status of the thyroid nodule?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Neck computed tomography","Thyroid scintigraphy","Thyroid ultrasound","Serum calcitonin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and biochemical evidence of thyrotoxicosis with a palpable thyroid nodule. The suppressed thyroid stimulating hormone with elevated free thyroid hormones indicates hyperthyroidism, and determining whether the nodule is responsible for the hormone excess is crucial for management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to determine the functional status of a thyroid nodule in a person with thyrotoxicosis. It uses a radioactive tracer to assess whether the nodule is hyperfunctioning (hot), hypofunctioning (cold), or normal (warm). This distinction is important because hyperfunctioning nodules are rarely malignant and require different management compared to non-functioning nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the best initial test for anatomical characterisation of thyroid nodules, including size, composition, and suspicious features, which can be graded according to TI-RADS criteria. However, it does not provide information about the functional status of the nodule, which is critical in the context of suppressed thyroid stimulating hormone and thyrotoxicosis. Note, a hot nodule should not have TI-RADS criteria applied thus the first step should be thyroid scintigraphy to determine functional status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for cytological assessment of thyroid nodules, especially those with suspicious ultrasound features or in euthyroid patients. In the setting of suppressed thyroid stimulating hormone, a functioning nodule is unlikely to be malignant, so biopsy is not the first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck computed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for assessment of large goitres with compressive symptoms or suspected local invasion. It does not provide functional information about thyroid nodules and is not routinely used in the initial evaluation of thyrotoxicosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum calcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour marker for medullary thyroid carcinoma and is not indicated in the routine assessment of thyroid nodules unless there is a specific suspicion for this malignancy. It does not provide information about nodule function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid scintigraphy is the investigation of choice to assess the functional status of a thyroid nodule in the context of thyrotoxicosis.","Thyroid scintigraphy distinguishes between hyperfunctioning (hot), hypofunctioning (cold), and normal (warm) nodules, guiding further management.","Ultrasound provides anatomical detail but does not assess nodule function; biopsy is not first-line in hyperfunctioning nodules."],"references":["Iqbal A, Rehman A. Thyroid Uptake and Scan. [Updated 2022 Oct 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555978/","Thyroid disease: assessment and management. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2019 Nov 20. (NICE Guideline, No. 145.) Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK550859/","Lee JC, Khafagi FA. Thyroid scans. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Aug;41(8):584-6. PMID: 23145398. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23145398/","Calle S, Choi J, Ahmed S, Bell D, Learned KO. Imaging of the Thyroid: Practical Approach. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. 2021 Aug;31(3):265-284. doi: 10.1016/j.nic.2021.04.008. PMID: 34243863. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34243863/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91470"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22135"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91470"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-17T17:20:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T17:20:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15097"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109112"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"I